<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    The dropdown UX research (2026-06-01 report) materialized 13 cross-cutting
    paradigms into intents but flagged one as noted-but-unspecified: <strong>async pagination beyond simple
    load-more</strong> — cursor vs offset/keyset, "load earlier" / bidirectional, and windowing combined with
    async. This survey gathers the pagination-strategy literature, the WAI-ARIA APG <strong>Feed</strong>
    pattern, React Aria's <code>useAsyncList</code>, and the open feature-requests across the major libraries,
    then checks them against the standards the repo has shipped <em>since</em> the item was filed. It grounds
    the open forks in <a href="/backlog/018-dropdown-async-pagination-paradigm/">backlog&nbsp;#018</a>.
</p>

<h3>Recommendation (forks for #018)</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>No net-new contract.</strong> The item is largely overtaken: cursor/offset already lives in the
        <a href="/resources/pagination/">Custom Pagination</a> protocol, and windowing+async is already a
        composition of <a href="/intents/windowed-collection/">Windowed Collection</a>
        (<code>dataSource:&nbsp;infinite</code>) over <a href="/intents/loader/">Loader</a>
        (<code>loadingMore</code>). The dropdown <em>composes</em> these; it does not re-specify them.</li>
    <li><strong>Fetch trigger:</strong> wire Collection Operations' <code>advance:&nbsp;manual&nbsp;|&nbsp;auto</code>
        onto the autocomplete member, default <code>auto</code> (scroll sentinel), with a manual "Load more"
        row as the keyboard / screen-reader fallback.</li>
    <li><strong>Load-earlier:</strong> <strong>forward-only</strong> for the family. The protocol exposes
        <code>previous()</code>, but top-loading is a Feed/chat/inbox paradigm, not a dropdown one — no
        surveyed library implements it in a combobox listbox.</li>
    <li><strong>Unknown-total a11y:</strong> adopt the Feed pattern — <code>aria-setsize="-1"</code> while the
        total is unknown, <code>aria-busy</code> during batch insert — as the progressive-load rule Windowed
        Collection currently omits.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 — the item is largely overtaken by work landed since 2026-06-01</h3>
<p>
    The item was filed off the dropdown report's open-question&nbsp;#3. Most of what it asks for now exists:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>cursor vs offset</strong> → the <a href="/resources/pagination/">Custom Pagination</a> protocol
        models <code>strategy:&nbsp;'offset'&nbsp;|&nbsp;'page'&nbsp;|&nbsp;'cursor'</code> with the
        cross-layer constraint baked in.</li>
    <li><strong>windowing + async</strong> → <a href="/intents/windowed-collection/">Windowed Collection</a>'s
        <code>dataSource:&nbsp;infinite</code> "composes the Loader <code>loadingMore</code> state", and Loader
        names Windowed Collection back — the two reference each other.</li>
    <li><strong>load-more lifecycle</strong> → Loader's <code>loadingMore</code> state (announced progress row
        at the list end, never a blocking overlay).</li>
    <li><strong>bidirectional API</strong> → the protocol's <code>previous()</code> + <code>hasPrevious</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    So #018 is <em>not</em> "design a new contract." It is the narrower call: does the family need any new
    standard, or does it just compose the three that exist — and what family-specific gaps remain?
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 — cursor / offset / keyset is a backend strategy with a UX consequence, already modeled</h3>
<p>
    The pagination literature is unanimous: <strong>offset/page</strong> is the only strategy yielding a known
    <code>total</code>, so it alone drives jump-to-page and a "showing&nbsp;21–40&nbsp;of&nbsp;500" range label —
    at the cost of slow deep pages and rows skipped/duplicated under concurrent writes.
    <strong>Cursor/keyset</strong> (pass the last-seen sort key) is fast at any depth and stable under writes
    but exposes <em>no total</em> — only <code>next()</code>/<code>previous()</code>, forcing an append /
    prev-next UX. This is exactly the model in the <a href="/resources/pagination/">Custom Pagination</a>
    resource. <strong>Nothing is left to specify</strong>, and it correctly lives at the resource (technical)
    layer, not as a UX intent — per the repo's intents-are-UX-only rule.
</p>

<h3>Finding 3 — <code>filtering</code> vs <code>loadingMore</code>: two distinct async states, both modeled</h3>
<p>
    A combobox fires two different async events, and Loader already enumerates both:
    <strong><code>filtering</code></strong> (re-query on new filter text — keeps prior results visible,
    debounced, stale resolutions dropped via the version token) and
    <strong><code>loadingMore</code></strong> (fetch the next page of the <em>same</em> query on scroll).
    React Aria's <code>useAsyncList</code> is the reference implementation of exactly this split: one
    <code>load({signal, cursor, filterText})</code> function where a changed <code>filterText</code> re-filters
    from page one and a present <code>cursor</code> appends the next page, with the
    <code>signal</code>&nbsp;<code>AbortSignal</code> cancelling stale in-flight requests. This corroborates the
    repo's two-state model — nothing new to add.
</p>

<h3>Finding 4 — the genuinely-open family gaps (the real forks)</h3>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Fetch trigger (fork&nbsp;2):</strong> Collection Operations has
        <code>advance:&nbsp;manual&nbsp;|&nbsp;auto</code> ("infinite scroll = append + auto") but it lives on
        grids, never wired onto the autocomplete member. Every surveyed library defaults to scroll-triggered
        auto-load (React Aria <code>onLoadMore</code>; the MUI/Fluent/SAP requests all assume infinite scroll),
        with a manual "Load more" row as the accessible fallback.</li>
    <li><strong>Load-earlier (fork&nbsp;3):</strong> the protocol has <code>previous()</code>, but top-loading
        (growing upward, preserving scroll anchor) is a <em>feed/chat/inbox</em> paradigm. No surveyed dropdown
        library implements it; the listbox is forward-append, and top-loading reintroduces the
        "scroll&nbsp;jumps&nbsp;to&nbsp;top&nbsp;on&nbsp;append" bug libraries fight hardest to avoid. The family
        default is forward-only; load-earlier belongs to a future Feed block.</li>
    <li><strong>Unknown-total a11y (fork&nbsp;4):</strong> Windowed Collection mandates <code>aria-setsize</code>
        = full count, but that assumes the count is <em>known</em>. Under cursor pagination it is unknown until
        the last page. The WAI-ARIA <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/feed/">Feed pattern</a>
        gives the platform answer: <code>aria-setsize="-1"</code> when the total is indeterminate, with
        <code>aria-busy="true"</code> during a batch insert flipped to <code>false</code> on completion.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Finding 5 — async option-pagination is community-driven, not native; no library treats it as solved</h3>
<p>
    Across <a href="https://github.com/mui/material-ui/issues/18450">MUI</a>,
    <a href="https://github.com/microsoft/fluentui/issues/31261">Fluent</a>,
    <a href="https://github.com/SAP/ui5-webcomponents/issues/6483">SAP UI5</a>,
    <a href="https://github.com/mui/base-ui/issues/3719">Base UI</a>, and
    <a href="https://github.com/radix-ui/primitives/issues/894">Radix</a>, "paginated / infinite-scroll
    combobox" is an <em>open feature request</em>, not a shipped primitive. React Aria
    (<code>useAsyncList</code> + <code>onLoadMore</code> + <code>ListBoxLoadMoreItem</code>) is the outlier with
    a first-class answer. The recurring bug everyone hits is
    <a href="https://github.com/mui/material-ui/issues/30249">scroll-resets-to-top-on-append</a> — which is why
    forward-append with a preserved scroll anchor is the safe family default, and why the active-always-mounted
    invariant Windowed Collection already mandates carries the load here.
</p>

<h3>Finding 6 — there is no native async combobox pagination</h3>
<p>
    Native <code>&lt;select&gt;</code> renders its full <code>&lt;option&gt;</code> set eagerly; there is no
    platform mechanism for progressively fetching options. So async pagination is necessarily an ARIA-composed
    custom-element concern, and the native-first baseline degrades to a fully-materialized list. This keeps the
    decision firmly in compose-existing-standards territory rather than waiting on a platform primitive.
</p>

